&gt; From a recent Yahoo! science news article:
&gt;
&gt; &quot;Unexpectedly, the lemurs could remember sequences.
&gt; For instance, they showed they could remember the
&gt; order of appearance of random images by touching them
&gt; in order when they reappeared as a group.&quot;
&gt;
&gt; I think that NEAT nets could be evolved that would
&gt; have the ability to remember, and then repeat back, a
&gt; series of random numbers.  (Of course, I may be
&gt; wrong.)
&gt;
&gt; Animals in nature are called upon to do that all the
&gt; time.  For example, when a small mammal migrates to a
&gt; new territory, he needs to leave his nest, explore for
&gt; food while remembering his route.  Then, to return
&gt; home, he recalls the route in reverse.
&gt;
&gt; Humans do it when they remember a new telephone number
&gt; for a short time.  Like when you say to someone:
&gt; Please dial 380-6637.  The person then dials the
&gt; number, perhaps never having heard it before.  Clearly
&gt; he had to memorize it and then recall it, even if it
&gt; is forgotten a few minutes later.
&gt;
&gt; I think this is a worthwhile challenge for recurrent ANNs.
